## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2014 Community Health Systems breach** — one of the largest healthcare breaches in US history at the time, affecting 4.5 million patients. Attackers exploited the **Heartbleed vulnerability** — a well-known flaw in the OpenSSL cryptographic library — to steal credentials and gain access to the network.

What made this case relevant to today's topic is the timeline. The Heartbleed vulnerability was publicly disclosed in April 2014. Community Health Systems was breached between April and June of that same year. The vulnerability was known. Patches were available. The risk was identifiable through a basic risk assessment process. But the organization had not assessed, prioritized, and remediated the vulnerability quickly enough to prevent the breach.

That pattern — known vulnerability, available patch, delayed response — comes up repeatedly in breach investigations. Risk assessment exists specifically to catch these situations before they become incidents. The process I worked through today, applied consistently and honestly, would have flagged Heartbleed as a critical risk requiring immediate patching. Whether the organization acts on that assessment is a governance question. But you cannot act on a risk you have not identified.

